{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15104"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.15,0.19,0.15,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19011"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing radical prostatectomy for prostate cancer, prostate specific antigen (PSA) levels are monitored to detect disease recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes PSA monitoring after radical prostatectomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biochemical recurrence is defined as PSA \u22650.2 ng/mL in two consecutive measurements","PSA levels should remain detectable but stable","PSA levels can take 6 months to become undetectable","PSA levels naturally fluctuate between 0.1-0.3 ng/mL post-surgery","PSA levels should decrease gradually over 12 months"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter radical prostatectomy, PSA levels should become undetectable (\u0026lt;0.1 ng/mL) within 6 weeks since all prostate tissue has been removed. \u003Cstrong\u003EBiochemical recurrence is defined as PSA \u22650.2 ng/mL in two consecutive measurements\u003C/strong\u003E, indicating possible disease recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is incorrect that \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA levels should remain detectable but stable\u003C/strong\u003E or that \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA levels can take 6 months to become undetectable\u003C/strong\u003E. The notion that \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA levels naturally fluctuate between 0.1-0.3 ng/mL post-surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is false - they should be undetectable. The statement that \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA levels should decrease gradually over 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the decrease should be rapid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["After radical prostatectomy, prostate specific antigen (PSA) should become undetectable (\u003C0.1 ng/mL) within 6 weeks","Biochemical recurrence after prostatectomy is defined as PSA \u22650.2 ng/mL in two consecutive measurements"],"references":["Ilic D, Djulbegovic M, Jung JH, Hwang EC, Zhou Q, Cleves A, Agoritsas T, Dahm P. Prostate cancer screening with prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test: a systematic review and meta-analysis. BMJ. 2018 Sep 5;362:k3519. doi: 10.1136/bmj.k3519. PMID: 30185521; PMCID: PMC6283370.","Merriel SWD, Pocock L, Gilbert E, Creavin S, Walter FM, Spencer A, Hamilton W. Systematic review and meta-analysis of the diagnostic accuracy of prostate-specific antigen (PSA) for the detection of prostate cancer in symptomatic patients. BMC Med. 2022 Feb 7;20(1):54. doi: 10.1186/s12916-021-02230-y. PMID: 35125113; PMCID: PMC8819971.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-16T21:13:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-16T21:14:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85612"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null